Introduction¶

Soccer Database from Kaggle¶

This soccer database comes from Kaggle and is well suited for data analysis and machine learning. It contains data for soccer matches, players, and teams from several European countries from 2008 to 2016. This dataset is quite extensive, and we encourage you to read more about it here.

  • The database is stored in a SQLite database.

Through this report, we will wrangle, clean and explore the data to answer some interesting questions :

  1. Is there a relationship between (Points) and (Goals for and Goals against) over different seasons ?
  2. What is the performance of each team over season ?
  3. Which teams have the worst defense for each season?
  4. Which teams have the best defense for each season?
  5. Which teams have the worst attack for each season?
  6. Which teams have the best attack for each season?

Now, let's start our journy !

# Now we will calculate the points for each team per match as 3 points means that the home team win ,
# 0 points means that the home team lose and 1 means that it is tie
home_points = []
away_points = []
for index, row in df.iterrows():
    if(row['home_team_goal'] > row['away_team_goal']):
      home_points.append(3)
      away_points.append(0)
    elif(row['home_team_goal'] < row['away_team_goal']):
      home_points.append(0)
      away_points.append(3)
    else:
      home_points.append(1)
      away_points.append(1)

df['home_points'] = home_points
df['away_points'] = away_points

# get_team_statistics function helps us to calculate goals for , goals against and points for all team in a selected league and season
# and it returns a dataframe contains all the teams in the selected season, the season, the goals for, the goals against and the points .

def get_team_statistics(df,season,league):
  premier_league = list(df[(df['league'] == league) & 
                           (df['season'] == season)]['home_team'].unique())

  sum_goals = df.groupby(['league','season','home_team','away_team']).agg({'home_team_goal': 'sum', 'away_team_goal': 'sum'})
  sum_goals.reset_index(inplace= True)

  goals_over_season = []
  for team in premier_league:
    team_name = sum_goals[(sum_goals['league'] == league) & 
                          (sum_goals['season'] == season) & 
                          ((sum_goals['home_team'] == team)| (sum_goals['away_team'] == team))]

    team_home = team_name[team_name['home_team'] == team]
    team_away = team_name[team_name['away_team'] == team]
    goals_over_season.append(team_home['home_team_goal'].sum() + team_away['away_team_goal'].sum())
  
  goals_against_over_season = []
  for team in premier_league:
    team_name = sum_goals[(sum_goals['league'] == league) & 
                          (sum_goals['season'] == season) & 
                          ((sum_goals['home_team'] == team)| (sum_goals['away_team'] == team))]

    team_home = team_name[team_name['home_team'] != team]
    team_away = team_name[team_name['away_team'] != team]
    goals_against_over_season.append(team_home['home_team_goal'].sum() + team_away['away_team_goal'].sum())
  
  sum_points = df.groupby(['league','season','home_team','away_team']).agg({'home_points': 'sum', 'away_points': 'sum'})
  sum_points.reset_index(inplace= True)

  points_over_season = []
  for team in premier_league:
    team_name = sum_points[(sum_points['league'] == league) & 
                           (sum_points['season'] == season) & 
                           ((sum_points['home_team'] == team)|(sum_points['away_team'] == team))]
    team_home = team_name[team_name['home_team'] == team]
    team_away = team_name[team_name['away_team'] == team]
    points_over_season.append(team_home['home_points'].sum() + team_away['away_points'].sum())
  
  team_statistics = pd.DataFrame({'team': premier_league,'season':season,'goals_for':goals_over_season,'points':points_over_season,
                                  'goals_against':goals_against_over_season})
  return team_statistics

1. Is there a relationship between (Points) and (Goals for and Goals against) over different seasons ?¶

In [26]:
# feature_distribution_plot function plots a histogram of our continuous variable points, goals for, goals against
# using histplot function from seaborn 
def feature_distribution_plot(df, feature):
  plt.figure(figsize=(15,6));
  sns.histplot(x = feature,data = df, bins= 30);
  plt.xlabel(feature, fontsize = 12);
  plt.title(feature + ' over Seasons', fontsize = 20);
  plt.grid();

# plot_relations_to_points function plots the relationship between points and any of our features 
# using scatterplot function from seaborn 
def plot_relations_to_points(df, feature):
  plt.figure(figsize=(15,6));
  sns.scatterplot(x = feature, y = 'points', data = df);
  plt.xlabel(feature +' '+ 'for all season', fontsize = 12);
  plt.ylabel('Points', fontsize = 12);
  plt.title(feature +' '+ 'vs Points for all season', fontsize = 20);
  plt.grid();

# Now we will plot three indicators (points, goals for, goals against) from which we can get 
# the differences of performance for each team for all seasons it participated in the league
team_index = range(33)
team_names = list(df['team'].unique())
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20,50));
for team_num,team in zip(team_index,team_names):
  plt.subplot(11,3, team_num+1);
  plt.plot(df[df['team'] == team]['season'],df[df['team'] == team]['goals_for'],marker = 'o', label = 'goals for');
  plt.plot(df[df['team'] == team]['season'],df[df['team'] == team]['goals_against'],marker = 'x', label = 'goals against');
  plt.plot(df[df['team'] == team]['season'],df[df['team'] == team]['points'],marker = 's', label = 'points');
  plt.ylim(15,120);
  plt.grid();
  plt.legend();
  plt.xticks(rotation= 20, fontsize = 12);
  plt.xlabel('Season', fontsize = 15);
  plt.ylabel('Goals for/Goals against/Points', fontsize = 14);
  plt.title(''.join([team,' Over Seasons']), fontsize = 17);
fig.suptitle('Teams Performance over Seasons', size = 20);
plt.tight_layout();
fig.subplots_adjust(top = 0.96)

From the above plot, we can get different insights as to

  • the number of seasons that each team participated in the England Premier League from 2009 to 2015
  • the difference in performance from season to season for each team according to the points the team gained.

3. Which teams have the worst defense for each season?¶

In [34]:
# defense_attack_over_seasons function help us to plot whether the best defense, the worst defense, the best attack, or the worst attack
# range_start and range_end determine exactly the number of teams we want to plot 
def defense_attack_over_seasons(dfs, y, ylabel, title, suptitle, range_start, range_end):
  season_index = range(9)
  fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,15));
  for num, season_teams in zip(season_index, dfs):
    season = str(season_teams['season'].unique())[2:-2]
    season_teams = season_teams.sort_values(y, ascending = False).iloc[range_start:range_end,:]
    plt.subplot(3,3,num+1);
    sns.barplot(x = 'team', y = y, data = season_teams);
    plt.xticks(rotation = 90);
    plt.xlabel('Team');
    plt.ylabel(ylabel);
    plt.title(title + ' ' + season+ ' Season');
  fig.suptitle(suptitle, size = 20);
  plt.tight_layout();
  fig.subplots_adjust(top=0.93)

    5. The best attack from 2013/2014 season to 2015/2016 season is Manchester City with about 103, 82 and 70 goals scored respectively.

  • We can conclude that the best attacks over all seasons are Chelsea and Manchester City with about 103 goals scored.
